  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison writes: &quot;I know not what weather you are having in Boston; but yesterday it was as hot and sultry as in July; and we experienced the full power of the heat in an excursion to Devil&apos;s Mountain, about six miles from friend Johnson&apos;s residence.&quot; Garrison praises the view from the top of Devil&apos;s Mountain. There was an argument on the train between an abolitionist and some pro-slavery men. Garrison read in the Boston Journal that the Faneuil Hall meeting was a great success. Charles Sumner was the principal speaker. Garrison comments about Sumner: &quot;His speech reads well, and no doubt was eloquently delivered. It seems that impudent and scatter-brained fellow, G. F. Train, undertook at the close to make a fool of himself, but was carried to the lock-up, with a shouting rabble after him as his sympathizers and backers.&quot; Garrison is going to Burlington, Vermont, and possibly Montreal.</subfield>
